Dear love, for nothing less than thee
Do seasons pale or rivers roam;
For every path and memory
Returns the exile to her home.

Not fleeting joy, nor wildest gold
Could fill the silent place you made;
With you, the night is fever-bright;
Without you, daylight seems to fade.

So take my longing, calm, and free:
It rests with none but you—complete;
Dear love, for nothing, nothing less
Than thee, my world admits defeat.

O God! Thou art my God alone;  
My days unfurl in winds unknown;  
Each step, awake, I search for skies  
That echo where Thy promise lies.  
Beneath the ancient vaulted dome  
Or restless streets, I wait, I roam;  
Throughout the world, throughout my days,  
I seek to meet Thee in Thy ways.

O God! Thou art my God alone;  
Not woods nor temples make Thee known;  
Yet in the hush between each breath,  
Thy silent love defeats my death.  
My heart awake at dawn's soft tone,  
Declares the throne that's Thine alone;  
To Thee, all mortal bonds are tied—  
My refuge, keeper, friend, and guide.

Within his grasp, once oceans churned with verse—  
Now tides recede, and salt denies his lips.  
Lines tumble, hollow, stutter, then disperse;  
Cold mornings bring no whisper to his quips.  

How thin the air that once became a storm,  
How deaf the world to singing’s subtle drum;  
He searches pockets, hands, a shattered form—  
No embers left to sow, no mantled hum.  

A poet loses—but loss is not an end;  
The silence hums, and ghosts become a friend.

Farewell, thou child of my right hand, and joy;
The cradle is silent, the echoes remain;
Petals of memories fragile, alloy
With longing’s lament, brimming sorrow’s main.
Your laughter, a bird-song that danced in the morning,
Still flutters in shadow where soft dreams deploy;
Now gone as the dew on forsaken adorning,
Farewell, my cherished, my right hand, my joy.

Adieu, O soldier! With honor adorned,
Your shadow sails out on the wind’s restless horn.
A tear in the rain, we are left with the sky;
The thunder and badges—no need to ask why.
Faith presses onward where memories dance;
You are the story of valor's romance.
We wait in the silence, we sing to the dew;
Faces remembered by morning anew.
Rest well on the fields where hope intertwines—
Adieu, O soldier! Until fate re-aligns.

The river led me to you though the way was hard and long,
I wandered banks wild with thistle, accompanied by birdsong.
Currents pulled my shadow deep, and moonlight marred my path;
Yet always to your presence keen, I journeyed through the aftermath.
Roots once tangled in the mud now mark the places I was strong;
How gentle then your hand in mine, the river humming us its song.
